From mike.kallies at gmail.com  Wed Oct  1 19:37:47 2014
From: mike.kallies at gmail.com (Mike)
Date: Wed, 1 Oct 2014 15:37:47 -0400
Subject: [GTALUG] Electronics Repair Shop
Message-ID: <2FE97AAE-5357-4B6E-80E5-33E2903F6653@gmail.com>

Hey everyone,

It's not entirely a Linux thing, but it's certainly a Toronto thing.

Anyone know a repair shop which will do Viewsonic Projectors?

I'm under extended third party warranty.  Viewsonic recommended somebody up in Northern Scarborough.   They have a $50 inspection fee (credited to your repair) which is... okay, but I hope I could find something more downtown, but equally reputable and affordable.

If there were no warranty, I would crack it open and look for capacitors :-)

If the estimate exceeds the value, I pay the $50, but I send the paperwork off to the insurance company and collect the purchase price.   So reputable means they'll get the estimate close, they've done viewsonic warranty work, have nice looking paper and accept credit cards.

Thanks,

-Mike





From tisdall at gmail.com  Thu Oct  2 13:49:58 2014
From: tisdall at gmail.com (Tim Tisdall)
Date: Thu, 2 Oct 2014 09:49:58 -0400
Subject: [GTALUG] Linux hosting
Message-ID: <CAGxYWpZrZNd2CyETq1XihMYZsdcOv-fejTOOPR=qdyJC2Ux+ag@mail.gmail.com>

I just wondering what people's current experiences are with cheap Linux web
hosting.  Right now I'm using vps.net and while they're cheap it's not
uncommon to have a 10hr downtime (which I'm in the middle of this
morning).  They don't seem to have any sort of basic monitoring of their
nodes to automatically be notified when a system is down (at least not on
an individual node level), they rely on me contacting them.

Has anyone had experience with digitalocean or linode for fairly long term
hosting?  I've only used digitalocean for occasional VPN use but have had
no issues.

-Tim
